        "retrievalContexts": [
          "Phishing Attacks in Healthcare (MediSure Health Systems)\n\nReal-time threat detection can identify unusual login attempts on electronic health record systems.\nIt can monitor network traffic for suspicious email activity, blocking phishing attempts before they reach employees.",
          "Social Engineering in Banking (FinTrust Banking Solutions)\n\nDetects unusual access patterns in online banking systems, flagging unauthorized attempts.\nAlerts IT staff when multiple failed login attempts occur in a short time.",
          "IoT Security in Robotics (NovaTech Robotics)\n\nMonitors network traffic for unauthorized access attempts on industrial robots.\nUses behavior-based anomaly detection to identify tampering with robotic control systems.",
          "Credential Stuffing in Streaming Services (StreamView Entertainment)\n\nIdentifies multiple login attempts from different locations using the same credentials.\nDetects large-scale automated attacks attempting to hijack user accounts.",
          "Examples of Good Responses:\nHow does real-time threat detection work?\n\n\"Real-time threat detection continuously monitors a network for unusual activity. It uses AI and machine learning to identify suspicious patterns, such as an employee logging in from two locations at the same time. Once a threat is detected, it can send alerts or even take automatic action, like blocking access.\"",
          "Examples of Good Responses:\n\nWhat vulnerabilities does it address?\n\"Real-time threat detection is especially useful against social engineering attacks, credential stuffing, and insider threats. It can flag unusual login behavior, detect unauthorized access attempts, and respond to threats before they escalate.\""
